1
00:00:00,583 --> 00:00:04,021
Every single-cell or Perturb-seq screen
hands you the same puzzle: dozens

2
00:00:04,021 --> 00:00:07,458
of gene programs, each just a ranked list,
none of them

3
00:00:07,458 --> 00:00:07,771
labeled.

4
00:00:07,771 --> 00:00:11,208
Working out what one program actually does
can eat a whole

5
00:00:11,208 --> 00:00:12,146
afternoon on PubMed.

6
00:00:12,146 --> 00:00:15,583
Enrichment gives you a vague heading; a
raw language model gives

7
00:00:15,583 --> 00:00:18,708
you a confident guess that sails right
past the biology.

8
00:00:18,708 --> 00:00:22,146
So we built the Gene Program Interpreter —
a Claude Skill

9
00:00:22,146 --> 00:00:25,583
that reads your programs the way an expert
would, in context,

10
00:00:25,583 --> 00:00:26,833
and shows its work.

11
00:00:27,125 --> 00:00:31,006
Two inputs go in: your weighted program
genes, and any regulators

12
00:00:31,006 --> 00:00:32,417
from a Perturb-seq screen.

13
00:00:32,708 --> 00:00:36,031
First it gives each program an identity —
organism, tissue, cell

14
00:00:36,031 --> 00:00:38,750
type, your conditions, and what these
cells normally do.

15
00:00:38,750 --> 00:00:42,073
The perturbed regulators keep their
direction, and STRING adds a conventional

16
00:00:42,073 --> 00:00:45,396
layer: enrichment, plus an interaction
network wiring each regulator to its

17
00:00:45,396 --> 00:00:45,698
targets.

18
00:00:45,698 --> 00:00:49,021
Now it's a regulatory response in a real
system, not a

19
00:00:49,021 --> 00:00:49,625
nameless list.

20
00:00:49,917 --> 00:00:50,740
Here's the engine.

21
00:00:50,740 --> 00:00:53,757
For every program, we spin up a separate
Claude agent —

22
00:00:53,757 --> 00:00:56,226
all in parallel — to dig through the
literature.

23
00:00:56,226 --> 00:00:59,243
Each one searches PubMed, OpenAlex, and
Crossref with its own tools,

24
00:00:59,243 --> 00:01:01,163
and only ever sees its own brief.

25
00:01:01,163 --> 00:01:04,181
Python runs the fan-out, so a whole screen
researches itself at

26
00:01:04,181 --> 00:01:06,375
once instead of one program at a time.

27
00:01:06,667 --> 00:01:09,841
Then every reference the agents bring back
is checked automatically —

28
00:01:09,841 --> 00:01:12,728
does it resolve, is it retracted, is it a
duplicate.

29
00:01:12,728 --> 00:01:15,902
Anything that doesn't hold up is dropped,
and disagreements and gaps

30
00:01:15,902 --> 00:01:18,500
are kept in plain sight rather than
smoothed over.

31
00:01:18,792 --> 00:01:22,175
Now it all comes together — the verified
papers, the context,

32
00:01:22,175 --> 00:01:25,558
the genes and regulators, the database
evidence — through Anthropic's Batch

33
00:01:25,558 --> 00:01:28,942
API, which writes each program up as clean
functional modules with

34
00:01:28,942 --> 00:01:31,402
a name that fits across the whole set.

35
00:01:31,402 --> 00:01:32,325
It's candid, too.

36
00:01:32,325 --> 00:01:35,708
Click any claim and the real paper opens
in one tap.

37
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:37,878
And here's a real result.

38
00:01:37,878 --> 00:01:42,010
Program 22 comes back as fructose-driven
lipogenesis — and the giveaway

39
00:01:42,010 --> 00:01:43,136
is its regulator.

40
00:01:43,136 --> 00:01:47,268
Mlxipl, or ChREBP, the master carbohydrate-response
transcription factor, switches the program

41
00:01:47,268 --> 00:01:51,400
on, and the evidence connects it directly
to Khk for fructose,

42
00:01:51,400 --> 00:01:54,405
Pklr for glycolysis, and Fasn for fat
synthesis.

43
00:01:54,405 --> 00:01:58,536
So this isn't a vague "lipid metabolism"
label — it's the

44
00:01:58,536 --> 00:02:01,917
fructose-to-fat pathway, pinned down by
what actually drives it.

45
00:02:02,208 --> 00:02:04,952
And the best part is how little it asks of
you.

46
00:02:04,952 --> 00:02:07,696
A few minutes to set up, and then it runs
itself.

47
00:02:07,696 --> 00:02:10,440
Describe your biology once — a short
context block — and

48
00:02:10,440 --> 00:02:12,935
the same Skill handles the whole pipeline
without touching code.

49
00:02:12,935 --> 00:02:15,679
It works through a whole screen in
parallel while you step

50
00:02:15,679 --> 00:02:15,929
away.

51
00:02:15,929 --> 00:02:18,673
The days you'd spend chasing references
become a hands-off pass —

52
00:02:18,673 --> 00:02:21,417
so your time goes back to the science, not
the searching.
